@David

It's a variant of French fée, "fairy". It's been in English as "fay" for a long time, with a conventional plural "fays".

I get the impression that the variant "fae" was coined specifically for fantasy writing, for the same reason we have "dwarves" in that context, instead of the usual "dwarfs"; and "elvish" instead of "elfin"---to shake the concept loose from its more cartoonish, Tinkerbellish, associations, and seek back to the mythological roots, in which fairies were not entirely pleasant or harmless entities.

@David

"Faerie" is an antique variant of "fairy", perhaps familiar from Spenser's "Faerie Queene". (I've seen it suggested that even in Spenser's day it was an archaic spelling, but that's well above my philological paygrade.)

Anyway... "faerie" now seems to have been recruited to signify "the realm of the fae", which I rather like.

