The line "Or easy gold at the hand of fae or elf" is from Robert Frost's poem "Mowing". It contrasts the practical work of mowing with the fantasy of a magical and effortless reward, suggesting the true value lies in honest labor. The phrase implies a rejection of fairy tale promises of wealth and ease, emphasizing the value of the work itself, not just the potential reward.

